In N 0. 577 Richard de Pei-cy de Dunsley, defining the extent of his grant to the Herrnitage, employs these termst—“cum his divisis, scil. totam terram meam de Midethet a baleo qui est inter vandelas domenii mei et vandelas hominnm meorum per cilium montis de Mnlgrif, etc.'’ Probably a “ wandale,” naudelu, vandayla, or “wandaile,” as in the present deed, was a single division, share, or “ deal '' of the large open arable field of any given township. Such fields are only just extinct in this part of North Yorkshire, and one of them was still extant at Staithes a few years ago, in which the low banks of division—‘⁸ balks'’ of No. 577—still stood boldly up.
